-- India's Stocks Post Asia's Biggest Gain as Outlook For Earnings Improves
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w   a n d   R u c h i k a   T u l s h y a n
-- 2010-10-21T10:59:38Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-21/india-s-stocks-post-first-gain-in-three-days-as-earnings-outlook-improves.html
India’s stocks rose the most in a
week, posting the biggest gain in Asia.  Tata Consultancy
Services Ltd.  and the nation’s biggest software developers led
gains on optimism corporate earnings are rebounding.  Tata Consultancy, the largest software services exporter,
increased for the first time in three days ahead of its earnings
report today.  Power Grid Corp. of India Ltd. , the biggest
transmission company, climbed the most in two weeks after
second-quarter profit jumped 42 percent.  Ashok Leyland Ltd. , the
second-biggest commercial vehicle maker, gained for the third
day after its profit rose 88 percent.  “In technology, the growth momentum continues very well,”
said Jitendra Sriram, who manages $750 million as head of
equities at HSBC Asset Management (India) Pvt. in Mumbai.
“Overall earnings have been as expected. We continue to be
positive on the domestic companies like autos and capital
goods.”  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 388.43, or 2 percent, to 20,260.58 as of the 3:30 p.m.
close in Mumbai. The gauge has gained 27 percent from the May 25
low, approaching the record closing high of 20,873.33 on Jan. 8,
2008. This year’s 16 percent rally makes the  Sensex  the best
performer among the world’s 10 biggest stock markets.  Global funds have been net buyers of stocks for 35 trading
days, the longest run of inflows in more than five years since
the 40-day period ended Aug. 9, 2005, according to data compiled
by Bloomberg.  The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National Stock Exchange rose
2 percent to 6,101.50. The  BSE 200 Index  increased 1.8 percent
to 2,576.98.  Tata Consultancy  Tata Consultancy added 2.4 percent to 986.2 rupees. The
company’s profit may increase 23 percent to 19.9 billion rupees,
according to average of 35 analysts’ estimates compiled by
Bloomberg. Rival Infosys Technologies Ltd. climbed 1.9 percent
to 3,034.45.  Wipro Ltd. , the third-biggest, increased 1.3
percent to 470.15 rupees.  Power Grid increased 1.3 percent to 105.6 rupees, its
biggest gain since Oct. 5. Ashok Leyland rose 1.4 percent to
76.55 rupees.  State-run Gujarat State Fertilizers & Chemicals Ltd. surged
7.7 percent to 369.6 rupees, its highest close in 18 years after
saying second-quarter profit more than doubled. Net income rose
to 2.07 billion rupees ($47 million) in the three months ended
Sept. 30 from 772 million rupees a year earlier.  Earnings Optimism  “The earnings are going to drive the markets,” said
 Kishor Ostwal , managing director of CNI Research (India) Ltd., a
publicly traded equities research provider in Mumbai.
“Investors would like to put their money in companies whose
earnings growth would be robust. Foreign investors have been
buying shares even on days when markets have fallen. This shows
they are optimistic on Indian company earnings.”  Local shares also gained as the nation’s food inflation
slowed to a four-week low as the heaviest monsoon rainfall in
three years boosted production of rice and corn.  The Reserve Bank of India is relying on lower farm prices
to cool the benchmark wholesale-price inflation rate to 6
percent by March 31 from 8.62 percent in September. The bank,
which has raised interest rates five times this year, is due to
release its next monetary policy statement on Nov. 2.  Hindustan Unilever Ltd. , biggest household products maker,
jumped 4.5 percent to 306.45 rupees.  ITC Ltd. , the biggest
cigarette company which is also in the agriculture business,
surged 3.8 percent to 174.35 rupees, the most in a month.  Overseas  investors  bought a net  3.41 billion rupees  ($77
million) of Indian equities on Oct. 19, extending this year’s
record inflows to 1.084 trillion rupees, according to the
nation’s market regulator.  To contact the reporter on this story:
